Author:
Vol / Page: 88
Edition:
Quote: Before the early seventies, the tiny native New Zealand rock oyster (<i>saccostrea glomerata</i>) clung to the rocks around the coastal shoreline and commercial  farming of the species was not highly profitable... The Pacific oyster which has overtaken the rock oyster and is now widely known as 'rock oyster' tends to be much larger, milder and is often quite creamy in texture.
